1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,280
Let's understand Conditional Co-Ablation — a way to find the hidden backup parts of a model's reasoning, from the ground up.

2
00:00:08,280 --> 00:00:12,200
First, the problem — and why it has stayed hidden.

3
00:00:12,200 --> 00:00:16,360
A language model reads a sentence and predicts the next word.

4
00:00:16,360 --> 00:00:23,000
Inside, small components called attention heads each carry out a little piece of that computation.

5
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:27,990
Here, a few heads copy the name Mary to the output as the prediction.

6
00:00:27,990 --> 00:00:32,310
The specific heads that carry one behavior are called its circuit.

7
00:00:32,310 --> 00:00:40,180
To find them, researchers delete a component and watch how much the answer changes. A big drop means it mattered.

8
00:00:40,180 --> 00:00:43,420
But here is the trap that motivates our work.

9
00:00:43,420 --> 00:00:49,370
Delete an important head, and a dormant backup silently takes over and re-routes the answer.

10
00:00:49,370 --> 00:00:58,750
The output barely changes. So the deleted head looks unimportant — and the backup, silent before, looks unimportant too.

11
00:00:58,750 --> 00:01:04,900
Deleting a group is not the sum of deleting its parts, and standard scoring misses both sides.

12
00:01:04,900 --> 00:01:14,620
This is not a curiosity. Interpretability is used to attribute behavior, to remove unwanted capabilities, and to prune models.

13
00:01:14,620 --> 00:01:20,570
When the importance score is wrong, every one of those tools inherits the same blind spot.

14
00:01:20,570 --> 00:01:22,960
So we change what we measure.

15
00:01:22,960 --> 00:01:27,780
CoAx fixes this with one idea: don't score a unit on its own.

16
00:01:27,780 --> 00:01:32,870
Score how much its effect grows once the main parts have already been removed.

17
00:01:32,870 --> 00:01:37,740
A backup does almost nothing by itself — its effect is near zero.

18
00:01:37,740 --> 00:01:47,410
But once its partner is removed, its effect becomes large. That growth is the CoAx score, and it needs no labels and no gradients.

19
00:01:47,410 --> 00:01:52,400
For the simplest case — a pair of heads — there is a companion signal.

20
00:01:52,400 --> 00:02:03,900
Ablate each alone and little happens; ablate them together and the effect is far larger than the sum. That gap, the synergy, flags mutually-compensating pairs.

21
00:02:03,900 --> 00:02:08,830
Measured over every pair of heads, the interactions reveal a hidden module:

22
00:02:08,830 --> 00:02:16,320
the main heads and their backups, wired in parallel — exactly what a one-head-at-a-time score cannot see.

23
00:02:16,320 --> 00:02:20,480
Now, the evidence — starting where we have ground truth.

24
00:02:20,480 --> 00:02:26,300
On a circuit with documented backups, we rank all the heads and check the eight known ones.

25
00:02:26,300 --> 00:02:35,990
Single-ablation scoring sits below chance at 0.33; even gradient methods built for self-repair top out at 0.82.

26
00:02:35,990 --> 00:02:42,490
CoAx reaches 0.91 — moving the backups from the blind spot to the top of the ranking.

27
00:02:42,490 --> 00:02:52,850
Head by head, it is the same eight backups seen two ways: near the bottom under first-order saliency, and at the top under conditional co-ablation.

28
00:02:52,850 --> 00:03:03,510
And they really are backups. As we remove the main heads one by one, the discovered heads wake up and start writing the answer, while random heads stay flat.

29
00:03:03,510 --> 00:03:13,480
The answer's direct attribution hands off to them, and freezing their dormant activations removes fifty-five percent of the self-repair — proof they cause it.

30
00:03:13,480 --> 00:03:24,390
Zoom into a single backup: it is silent on the clean model, yet it already reads the correct name, and becomes load-bearing only once its primary is gone.

31
00:03:24,390 --> 00:03:29,120
Because they are load-bearing, the recovered backups repair the tools.

32
00:03:29,120 --> 00:03:38,110
Take attribution. Ablating the primaries alone changes the answer by only 0.22 — self-repair hides the rest.

33
00:03:38,110 --> 00:03:45,730
Add the recovered backups and the true effect, 1.76, reappears: the part the redundancy masked.

34
00:03:45,730 --> 00:03:57,430
And re-measuring the score as heads are removed gives a repair-aware pruning order that stays nearest the dense model, from 124 million to 7 billion parameters.

35
00:03:57,430 --> 00:04:02,150
Finally — is it one lucky circuit, or a general phenomenon?

36
00:04:02,150 --> 00:04:11,140
The same label-free method transfers to a second circuit, induction, across eight further models and six architecture families.

37
00:04:11,140 --> 00:04:24,170
It is honest about scope: where redundancy is shared among co-firing heads, input-side methods find them too, and on MLP-dominated circuits the head-level signal does not transfer.

38
00:04:24,170 --> 00:04:28,550
So a component's importance is not fixed — it is conditional.

39
00:04:28,550 --> 00:04:38,840
The parts that matter most are often the ones that stay silent until they are needed. Code, an interactive page, and the paper are linked on screen.
